The problem is that `IFormFile` buffers the entire request body into memory. Instead, read the raw request body stream and write it directly to disk.

**Solution: Stream directly from `Request.Body`**

```csharp
// Program.cs
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Disable the default form body size limit
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
{
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024; // 2 GB
});

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Disable request buffering so the stream isn't held in memory
    request.EnableBuffering(bufferThreshold: 1024 * 64); // optional: small memory threshold

    var filePath = Path.Combine(Path.GetTempPath(), $"{Guid.NewGuid()}.tmp");

    await using var fileStream = new FileStream(
        filePath, FileMode.Create, FileAccess.Write, FileShare.None,
        bufferSize: 81920, useAsync: true);

    await request.Body.CopyToAsync(fileStream);

    return Results.Ok(new { path = filePath, size = fileStream.Length });

}).DisableAntiforgery();

app.Run();
```

**If you need multipart form-data** (file + metadata), use `MultipartReader` to avoid buffering:

```csharp
app.MapPost("/upload-multipart", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    var boundary = request.GetMultipartBoundary()
        ?? throw new BadHttpRequestException("Not a multipart request");

    var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);
    MultipartSection? section;

    while ((section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync()) is not null)
    {
        if (ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(section.ContentDisposition, out var cd)
            && cd.IsFileDisposition())
        {
            var filePath = Path.Combine(Path.GetTempPath(), $"{Guid.NewGuid()}.tmp");
            await using var fs = File.Create(filePath);
            await section.Body.CopyToAsync(fs);
            return Results.Ok(new { file = cd.FileName.Value, path = filePath });
        }
    }

    return Results.BadRequest("No file found");

}).DisableAntiforgery();
```

**Key points:**

| Setting | Why |
|---------|-----|
| `MaxRequestBodySize = 2GB` | Kestrel rejects anything over 30MB by default |
| Avoid `IFormFile` | It buffers the full content into memory |
| `Request.Body.CopyToAsync` | Streams chunk-by-chunk (~81KB) to disk |
| `MultipartReader` | Parses boundaries without buffering the whole part |
| `DisableAntiforgery()` | Minimal APIs in .NET 8 enable antiforgery by default for form posts |

If you're behind IIS/HttpSys, also set `requestLimits maxAllowedContentLength` in `web.config` or the equivalent `MaxRequestBodySize` on that server.
